		<item>
 			<author>School of Languages - Sabanc&#305; University</author>			<title>Farewell to a filmmaker: Atif Yilmaz</title>
			<itunes:author>School of Languages - Sabanc&#305; University</itunes:author>			<itunes:image href="http://sl.sabanciuniv.edu/eng/PodCast/slpodcastlogo.jpg"/>			<pubDate>2006-08-18 14:29:28</pubDate>
			<description>Farewell to a filmmaker: Atif Yilmaz (1925-2006) Atif Yilmaz, who virtually forged the memory of an entire people in his films of every conceivable genre, put his stamp on Turkish cinema through hard work and constant innovation.

A film sometimes has a significance that is different, very different indeed, from what it sets out to depict. There are few people perhaps whose lives are changed by watching a film &amp;#8211;and they usually turn out to be directors or actors- but certain films become lodged in either the most vulnerable, or the most exuberant, times of a person&amp;#8217;s life. He is gone now, but some of Atif Yilmaz&amp;#8217;s films are not mere personal remembrances but a virtual repository of the memory of an entire society. Script by Berat Guncikan. Published  in Skylife Magazine 2006. Copyright permission granted by Skylife. Presenter: Mary Wynn Karatal. slpodcast@sabanciuniv.edu</description>
			<draft>false</draft>
			<enclosure url="http://sl.sabanciuniv.edu/eng/PodCast/files/podcast24.mp3" length="3192320" type="audio/mpeg"/>
		</item>
